node.title: Benefits of a high angle frog

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Matt Kenney on September 10, 2021.

node.text: Sunday I fly to Kansas City to teach a box making class for the @kansascitywoodworkersguild next week. These are tools I’m taking. If there is something you don’t see but think I should have (dividers, a leg or moxon vise, a marking knife, etc) feel free to point it out but also know that whatever it is I don’t need it to make boxes! 😂

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Matt Kenney on September 09, 2021.

node.text: Here’s a kumiko panel that I am shipping out today. This year has been super busy but I think I’ll have some time the next few months to get cranking in the shop again. I am teaching in KC next week but when I get back I have a credenza to finish and some other things I am excited for but can’t discuss right now. Last photo is of some artwork I recently did for the lovely and wonderful Sam, who’s birthday was earlier this week. (I also made the frame.) She’s by far the best thing that’s happened for me this year.

Photo by Matt Kenney on September 09, 2021.
Photo by Matt Kenney on September 06, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
Simple and beautiful. (at least I think so)
-
It’s a gorgeous September day in Connecticut. Perfect for Labor Day. I get to spend it celebrating the birthday of the most wonderful woman in the world, Sam. We’re going for a hike and then we’ll have ice cream cake with my kids. Hope you’re having a great day, too!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Matt Kenney on September 03, 2021.

node.text: Other than @philipmorleyfurniture, what’s your favorite tool? For me it’s my 1 in. wide @lienielsentoolworks chisel. Perfectly balanced. Excellent weight. Fits my hand wonderfully. It has become an extension of my arm in many regards. Love it.

node.text: Two weekends ago, another woodworker stopped by for some help cutting dovetails with a tablesaw. I like cutting them with a tablesaw because it allows me to more readily focus on what really matters: how the tails and pins fit together. That’s the hardest thing to teach. They should go together with hand pressure and still be tight. It’s far easier to learn this in person from someone that has experience fitting the joint well.

node.text: This is the joint I use to make decorative frames for kumiko panels. It’s a half lap joint with offset shoulders to fill the rabbet. The rabbet is exactly half the parts’ thickness and I leave the dado set at that height when I cut the cheeks. It’s super efficient and strong joint. I also like that the joiner lines, which are square, mirror the joinery lines in the kumiko panel’s frame.

node.text: I first experimented with kumiko in 2015. It was a small decision to do so, really, but that decision pushed a small pebble down a snowy slope, and over the last six years it’s picked up speed and mass, and now it’s an avalanche. I would not have financially survived COVID were it not for kumiko, and I wouldn’t have a book that’s been translated into three languages, either. Now there’s an online course with @domestika that has subtitles in seven or eight languages. (Link in profile for details.) It’s amazing how small decisions grow on their own, weaving together with other small decisions until one day you’ve made a wonderful life and career from them, and you end up somewhere you never even thought to imagine.

node.text: I’d be surprised if you’d missed it (because I’ve been tooted my own horn about it so much!), but in case you did: My @domestika kumiko course is now open for registration. In the course, I walk you through how to make the frame and patterns for a kumiko panel that I designed. The folks at @domestika do an awesome job creating their courses and telling a story while also providing excellent instruction. Check out the link in my profile for details. If you sign up for the class using that link, I see far more financial benefit than if you do it not using the link. A huge thanks to everyone that has signed up so far!

node.text: The kumiko panel that I show how to make in my course on @domestika uses my two favorite patterns: a “hashtag” spun 45º and the ads-no-ha. The hashtag one is so simply but creates a beautiful, complex pattern when rotated 45º. Check out the link in my profile for details about the course. So far, the response has been great! Thanks to everyone that has signed up so far!
